</m:semantics>
</m:math> 
 with the horizontal, friction is given by <m:math><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:msub><m:mi>f</m:mi><m:mrow><m:mtext>k</m:mtext></m:mrow></m:msub><m:mo stretchy="false">=</m:mo><m:msub><m:mi>μ</m:mi><m:mrow><m:mtext>k</m:mtext></m:mrow></m:msub></m:mrow><m:mstyle fontstyle="italic"><m:mrow><m:mtext>mg</m:mtext></m:mrow></m:mstyle><m:mspace width="0.15em"/><m:mtext>cos</m:mtext><m:mspace width="0.15em"/><m:mi>θ</m:mi></m:mrow></m:mrow><m:mrow/></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="StarMath 5.0"> size 12{f rSub { size 8{k} } =μ rSub { size 8{k} }  ital "mg""cos"θ} {}</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math>. All objects will slide down a slope with constant acceleration under these circumstances. Proof of this is left for this chapter’s Problems and Exercises.</para></example><note id="fs-id1244089"><label/><title>Take-Home Experiment</title>
      
      <para id="import-auto-id1165298740778">An object will slide down an inclined plane at a constant velocity if the net force on the object is zero. We can use this fact to measure the coefficient of kinetic friction between two objects. As shown in <link target-id="fs-id1704828"/>, the kinetic friction on a slope <m:math><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:msub><m:mi>f</m:mi><m:mrow><m:mtext>k</m:mtext></m:mrow></m:msub><m:mo stretchy="false">=</m:mo><m:msub><m:mi>μ</m:mi><m:mrow><m:mtext>k</m:mtext></m:mrow></m:msub></m:mrow><m:mstyle fontstyle="italic"><m:mrow><m:mtext>mg</m:mtext></m:mrow></m:mstyle><m:mspace width="0.25em"/><m:mtext>cos</m:mtext><m:mspace width="0.15em"/><m:mi>θ</m:mi></m:mrow></m:mrow><m:mrow/></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="StarMath 5.0"> size 12{f rSub { size 8{k} } =μ rSub { size 8{k} }  ital "mg""cos"θ} {}</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math>. The component of the weight down the slope is equal to <m:math><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mstyle fontstyle="italic"><m:mrow><m:mtext>mg</m:mtext></m:mrow></m:mstyle><m:mspace width="0.25em"/><m:mtext>sin</m:mtext><m:mspace width="0.15em"/><m:mi>θ</m:mi></m:mrow></m:mrow><m:mrow/></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="StarMath 5.0"> size 12{ ital "mg""sin"θ} {}</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math> (see the free-body diagram in <link target-id="import-auto-id1165296217411"/>). These forces act in opposite directions, so when they have equal magnitude, the acceleration is zero. Writing these out:</para><equation id="eip-387"><m:math>
          <m:semantics>
