        </m:math> 
      </equation><equation id="eip-368"><m:math><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:msub><m:mi>μ</m:mi><m:mrow><m:mtext>k</m:mtext></m:mrow></m:msub><m:mstyle fontstyle="italic"><m:mrow><m:mtext>mg</m:mtext></m:mrow></m:mstyle><m:mspace width="0.25em"/><m:mtext>cos</m:mtext><m:mspace width="0.25em"/><m:mrow><m:mi>θ</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">=</m:mo><m:mstyle fontstyle="italic"><m:mrow><m:mtext>mg</m:mtext></m:mrow></m:mstyle></m:mrow><m:mspace width="0.25em"/><m:mtext>sin</m:mtext><m:mspace width="0.25em"/><m:mi>θ</m:mi></m:mrow><m:mo>.</m:mo></m:mrow><m:mrow/></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="StarMath 5.0"> size 12{μ rSub { size 8{k} }  ital "mg""cos"θ= ital "mg""sin"θ} {}</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math></equation><para id="import-auto-id1165298535121">Solving for <m:math><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:msub><m:mi>μ</m:mi><m:mrow><m:mtext>k</m:mtext></m:mrow></m:msub></m:mrow><m:mrow/></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="StarMath 5.0"> size 12{μ rSub { size 8{k} } } {}</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math>, we find that</para><equation id="eip-680"><m:math><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:msub><m:mi>μ</m:mi><m:mrow><m:mtext>k</m:mtext></m:mrow></m:msub><m:mo stretchy="false">=</m:mo><m:mfrac><m:mrow><m:mstyle fontstyle="italic"><m:mrow><m:mtext>mg</m:mtext></m:mrow></m:mstyle><m:mspace width="0.25em"/><m:mtext>sin</m:mtext><m:mspace width="0.25em"/><m:mi>θ</m:mi></m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mstyle fontstyle="italic"><m:mrow><m:mtext>mg</m:mtext></m:mrow></m:mstyle><m:mspace width="0.25em"/><m:mtext>cos</m:mtext><m:mspace width="0.25em"/><m:mi>θ</m:mi></m:mrow></m:mfrac></m:mrow><m:mo stretchy="false">=</m:mo><m:mtext>tan</m:mtext></m:mrow><m:mspace width="0.25em"/><m:mi>θ</m:mi></m:mrow><m:mo>.</m:mo></m:mrow><m:mrow/></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="StarMath 5.0"> size 12{μ rSub { size 8{k} } = {  { ital "mg""sin"θ}  over  { ital "mg""cos"θ} } ="tan"θ} {}</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math></equation><para id="import-auto-id1165298860484">Put a coin on a book and tilt it until the coin slides at a constant velocity down the book. You might need to tap the book lightly to get the coin to move. Measure the angle of tilt relative to the horizontal and find <m:math><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:msub><m:mi>μ</m:mi><m:mrow><m:mtext>k</m:mtext></m:mrow></m:msub></m:mrow><m:mrow/></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="StarMath 5.0"> size 12{μ rSub { size 8{K} } } {}</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math>. Note that the coin will not start to slide at all until an angle greater than <m:math>
<m:semantics>
<m:mrow>

<m:mrow>
